[{"name":"humanity","pos":"noun","content":"<div class=\"entry\" sum=\"985\" hclass=\"entry\" hlength=\"8\" id=\"humanity\" htag=\"section\" sk=\"humanity: :0\" idm_id=\"000029167\"><div class=\"top-container\"><div class=\"top-g\" id=\"humanity_topg_1\"><div class=\"webtop\"><h1 class=\"headword\" hclass=\"headword\" ox5000=\"y\" htag=\"h1\" id=\"humanity_h_1\">humanity</h1> <span class=\"pos\" htag=\"span\" hclass=\"pos\">noun</span><div class=\"symbols\" htag=\"div\" hclass=\"symbols\"><a href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/wordlists/oxford3000-5000?dataset=english&amp;list=ox5000&amp;level=c1\"><span class=\"ox5ksym_c1\">&nbsp;</span></a></div><span class=\"phonetics\"> <div class=\"phons_br\" wd=\"humanity\" hclass=\"phons_br\" geo=\"br\" htag=\"div\"><div class=\"sound audio_play_button pron-uk icon-audio\" data-src-mp3=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/media/english/uk_pron/h/hum/human/humanity__gb_1.mp3\" data-src-ogg=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/media/english/uk_pron_ogg/h/hum/human/humanity__gb_1.ogg\" title=\"humanity pronunciation\n                    English\" style=\"cursor: pointer\" valign=\"top\">&nbsp;</div><span class=\"phon\">/hjuːˈmænəti/</span></div> <div class=\"phons_n_am\" hclass=\"phons_n_am\" wd=\"humanity\" geo=\"n_am\" htag=\"div\"><div class=\"sound audio_play_button pron-us icon-audio\" data-src-mp3=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/media/english/us_pron/h/hum/human/humanity__us_1.mp3\" data-src-ogg=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/media/english/us_pron_ogg/h/hum/human/humanity__us_1.ogg\" title=\"humanity pronunciation\n                    American\" style=\"cursor: pointer\" valign=\"top\">&nbsp;</div><span class=\"phon\">/hjuːˈmænəti/</span></div></span></div><a class=\"responsive_display_inline_on_smartphone link-right\" href=\"#relatedentries\">\n                            jump to other results\n                        </a></div></div><ol class=\"senses_multiple\" htag=\"ol\"><li class=\"sense\" ox5000=\"y\" htag=\"li\" cefr=\"c1\" id=\"humanity_sng_1\" hclass=\"sense\" sensenum=\"1\"><a class=\"open oup_icons\" title=\"Add to My Word Lists\"><span class=\"star-btn\" aria-hidden=\"true\">​</span></a><span class=\"sensetop\" hclass=\"sensetop\" htag=\"span\"><div class=\"symbols\" hclass=\"symbols\" htag=\"div\"><a href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/wordlists/oxford3000-5000?dataset=english&amp;list=ox5000&amp;level=c1\"><span class=\"ox5ksym_c1\">&nbsp;</span></a></div></span><span class=\"grammar\" hclass=\"grammar\" htag=\"span\">[uncountable]</span> <span class=\"def\" hclass=\"def\" htag=\"span\">people in general</span><ul class=\"examples\" htag=\"ul\" hclass=\"examples\"><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"x\">He was found guilty of crimes against humanity.</span></li></ul><div class=\"collapse\" htag=\"div\" hclass=\"collapse\"><span class=\"unbox\" id=\"humanity_unbox_1\" unbox=\"more_about\"><span class=\"box_title\">More About <span class=\"closed\">gender</span></span><span class=\"body\"><span class=\"unbox\">gender</span><span class=\"unbox\">Ways of talking about men and women</span><ul class=\"bullet\"><li class=\"li\">When you are writing or speaking English it is important to use language that includes both men and women equally. Some people may be very offended if you do not.</li></ul><span class=\"unbox\">The human race</span><ul class=\"bullet\"><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"eb\">Man</span> and <span class=\"eb\">mankind</span> have traditionally been used to mean ‘all men and women’. Many people now prefer to use <span class=\"eb\">humanity</span>, <span class=\"eb\">the human race</span>, <span class=\"eb\">human beings</span> or <span class=\"eb\">people</span>.</li></ul><span class=\"unbox\">Jobs</span><ul class=\"bullet\"><li class=\"li\">The suffix <span class=\"eb\">-ess</span> in names of occupations such as <span class=\"eb\">actress</span>, <span class=\"eb\">hostess</span> and <span class=\"eb\">waitress</span> shows that the person doing the job is a woman. Many people now avoid these. Instead you can use <span class=\"eb\">actor</span> or <span class=\"eb\">host</span> (although <span class=\"eb\">actress</span> and <span class=\"eb\">hostess</span> are still very common), or a neutral word, such as <span class=\"eb\">server</span> for <span class=\"ei\">waiter</span> and <span class=\"ei\">waitress</span>. </li><li class=\"li\">Many job names ending in <span class=\"ei\">-man</span> also have a female equivalent ending <span class=\"ei\">-woman</span> (eg <span class=\"eb\">postman/​postwoman</span>), but in some cases one equivalent is rarely or never used, especially in old-fashioned job names that were traditionally done by one sex (eg <span class=\"eb\">coalman</span>, <span class=\"eb\">washerwoman</span>). Other forms such as <span class=\"eb\">batswoman</span> and <span class=\"eb\">tradeswoman</span> are becoming more common as more women start to do these jobs.</li><li class=\"li\">Neutral words like <span class=\"eb\">assistant</span>, <span class=\"eb\">worker</span>, <span class=\"eb\">person</span> or <span class=\"eb\">officer</span> are now often used instead of <span class=\"ei\">-man</span> or <span class=\"ei\">-woman</span> in the names of jobs. For example, you can use <span class=\"eb\">police officer</span> instead of <span class=\"ei\">policeman</span> or <span class=\"ei\">policewoman</span>, and <span class=\"eb\">spokesperson</span> instead of <span class=\"ei\">spokesman</span> or <span class=\"ei\">spokeswoman</span>. Neutral words are very common in newspapers, on television and radio and in official writing, in both <span class=\"labels\" hclass=\"labels\" htag=\"span\">British English</span> and <span class=\"labels\" htag=\"span\" hclass=\"labels\">North American English</span>.</li><li class=\"li\">When talking about jobs that are traditionally done by the other sex, some people say: <span class=\"eb\">a male secretary</span>/<span class=\"eb\">nurse</span>/<span class=\"eb\">model</span> (NOT <span class=\"eb\">man</span>) or <span class=\"eb\">a woman</span>/<span class=\"eb\">female</span> <span class=\"eb\">doctor</span>/<span class=\"eb\">barrister</span>/<span class=\"eb\">driver</span>. However, this is now not usually done unless you need to emphasize which sex the person is, or it is still unusual for the job to be done by a man/​woman: <span class=\"unx\">My daughter prefers to see a woman doctor.</span><span class=\"unx\">They have a male nanny for their kids.</span><span class=\"unx\">a female racing driver</span></li></ul><span class=\"unbox\">Pronouns</span><ul class=\"bullet\"><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"eb\">He</span> used to be considered to cover both men and women: <span class=\"unx\">Everyone needs to feel he is loved.</span> This is not now acceptable. Instead, after <span class=\"eb\">everybody</span>, <span class=\"eb\">everyone</span>, <span class=\"eb\">anybody</span>, <span class=\"eb\">anyone</span>, <span class=\"eb\">somebody</span>, <span class=\"eb\">someone</span>, etc. one of the plural pronouns <span class=\"eb\">they</span>, <span class=\"eb\">them</span>, and <span class=\"eb\">their</span> is often used: <span class=\"unx\">Does everybody know what they want?</span><span class=\"unx\">Somebody’s left their coat here.</span><span class=\"unx\">I hope nobody’s forgotten to bring their passport with them.</span></li><li class=\"li\">It is now generally acceptable in writing and speech to use <span class=\"eb\">they</span>, <span class=\"eb\">them</span>, and <span class=\"eb\">their</span> to refer to a singular noun: <span class=\"unx\">When a guest arrives, they check in and we show them to their room.</span> However, some people prefer to use <span class=\"eb\">he or she</span>, <span class=\"eb\">his or her</span>, or <span class=\"eb\">him or her</span>: <span class=\"unx\">Everyone knows what’s best for him- or herself.</span> <span class=\"eb\">He/​she</span> or <span class=\"eb\">(s)he</span> can also be used in writing: <span class=\"unx\">If in doubt, ask your doctor. He/​she can give you more information.</span> (You may find that some writers just use ‘she’.) If these uses seem awkward, you can change the sentence and use a plural noun. Instead of saying: <span class=\"unx\">A baby cries when he or she is tired</span> you can say <span class=\"unx\">Babies cry when they are tired.</span></li><li class=\"li\">Some people now specify which pronouns they prefer to be used when they are referred to, usually according to their <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/gender-identity\" title=\"gender identity definition\"><span class=\"ndv\">gender identity</span></a>: <span class=\"unx\">I want to share with you that I am trans, and my pronouns are ‘they’ and ‘them’.</span></li></ul></span></span></div><div class=\"collapse\" htag=\"div\" hclass=\"collapse\"><span class=\"unbox\" unbox=\"extra_examples\" id=\"humanity_unbox_2\"><span class=\"box_title\">Extra Examples</span><ul class=\"examples\" htag=\"ul\" hclass=\"examples\"><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"unx\">All the streets around the temple were just a mass of humanity.</span></li><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"unx\">It is because I care about the future of humanity that I'm conducting this research.</span></li><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"unx\">She was told her son had died in the service of humanity.</span></li></ul></span></div>          \n</li><li class=\"sense\" ox5000=\"y\" htag=\"li\" id=\"humanity_sng_2\" cefr=\"c1\" hclass=\"sense\" sensenum=\"2\"><a class=\"open oup_icons\" title=\"Add to My Word Lists\"><span class=\"star-btn\" aria-hidden=\"true\">​</span></a><span class=\"sensetop\" htag=\"span\" hclass=\"sensetop\"><div class=\"symbols\" htag=\"div\" hclass=\"symbols\"><a href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/wordlists/oxford3000-5000?dataset=english&amp;list=ox5000&amp;level=c1\"><span class=\"ox5ksym_c1\">&nbsp;</span></a></div></span><span class=\"grammar\" hclass=\"grammar\" htag=\"span\">[uncountable]</span> <span class=\"def\" hclass=\"def\" htag=\"span\">the state of being a person rather than a god, an animal or a machine</span><ul class=\"examples\" hclass=\"examples\" htag=\"ul\"><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"x\">The story was used to emphasize the humanity of Jesus.</span></li><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"x\">united by a sense of common humanity</span></li></ul><div class=\"collapse\" hclass=\"collapse\" htag=\"div\"><span class=\"unbox\" id=\"humanity_unbox_3\" unbox=\"snippet\"><span class=\"box_title\">Oxford Collocations Dictionary</span><span class=\"body\"><span class=\"unbox\">adjective</span><ul class=\"collocs_list\"><li class=\"li\">great</li><li class=\"li\">true</li><li class=\"li\">common</li><li class=\"li\">…</li></ul><span class=\"xref_to_full_entry\">See <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/collocations/humanity\" title=\" definition in Collocations\n \">full entry</a></span></span></span></div>                                     <div class=\"parallax-container \" data-iaw=\"container\">\n        <div class=\"parallax-abs\">\n            <div id=\"ad_contentslot_1\" class=\"am-default contentslot parallax-fix\">\n                <script>iaw.cmd.push(function() { iaw.display('ad_contentslot_1'); });</script>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n             </li><li class=\"sense\" hclass=\"sense\" sensenum=\"3\" ox5000=\"y\" htag=\"li\" cefr=\"c1\" id=\"humanity_sng_3\"><a class=\"open oup_icons\" title=\"Add to My Word Lists\"><span class=\"star-btn\" aria-hidden=\"true\">​</span></a><span class=\"sensetop\" hclass=\"sensetop\" htag=\"span\"><div class=\"symbols\" hclass=\"symbols\" htag=\"div\"><a href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/wordlists/oxford3000-5000?dataset=english&amp;list=ox5000&amp;level=c1\"><span class=\"ox5ksym_c1\">&nbsp;</span></a></div></span><span class=\"grammar\" hclass=\"grammar\" htag=\"span\">[uncountable]</span> <span class=\"def\" hclass=\"def\" htag=\"span\">the quality of being kind to people and animals by making sure that they do not suffer more than is necessary; the quality of being <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/humane\" title=\"humane definition\"><span class=\"ndv\">humane</span></a></span><ul class=\"examples\" htag=\"ul\" hclass=\"examples\"><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"x\">The judge was praised for his courage and humanity.</span></li></ul> <span class=\"xrefs\" htag=\"span\" hclass=\"xrefs\" xt=\"opp\"><span class=\"prefix\">opposite</span> <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/inhumanity\" title=\"inhumanity definition\"><span class=\"xr-g\" href=\"inhumanity_e\" bord=\"n\"><span class=\"xh\">inhumanity</span></span></a></span><span class=\"topic-g\"><span class=\"prefix\">Topics </span><a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/personal-qualities?level=c1\" title=\"Topic personal-qualities\"><span class=\"topic\" href=\"l2:people:personal_qualities?cefr=c1\"><span class=\"topic_name\">Personal qualities</span><span class=\"topic_cefr\">c1</span></span></a></span><div class=\"collapse\" hclass=\"collapse\" htag=\"div\"><span class=\"unbox\" id=\"humanity_unbox_4\" unbox=\"snippet\"><span class=\"box_title\">Oxford Collocations Dictionary</span><span class=\"body\"><span class=\"unbox\">adjective</span><ul class=\"collocs_list\"><li class=\"li\">great</li><li class=\"li\">true</li><li class=\"li\">common</li><li class=\"li\">…</li></ul><span class=\"xref_to_full_entry\">See <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/collocations/humanity\" title=\" definition in Collocations\n \">full entry</a></span></span></span></div>      </li><li class=\"sense\" sensenum=\"4\" hclass=\"sense\" cefr=\"c1\" id=\"humanity_sng_4\" htag=\"li\" ox5000=\"y\"><a class=\"open oup_icons\" title=\"Add to My Word Lists\"><span class=\"star-btn\" aria-hidden=\"true\">​</span></a><span class=\"sensetop\" htag=\"span\" hclass=\"sensetop\"><div class=\"symbols\" hclass=\"symbols\" htag=\"div\"><a href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/wordlists/oxford3000-5000?dataset=english&amp;list=ox5000&amp;level=c1\"><span class=\"ox5ksym_c1\">&nbsp;</span></a></div></span><div class=\"variants\" type=\"alt\" hclass=\"variants\" htag=\"div\"><span class=\"v-g\"><span class=\"v\">(the) humanities</span></span></div> <span class=\"grammar\" hclass=\"grammar\" htag=\"span\">[plural]</span> <span class=\"def\" hclass=\"def\" htag=\"span\">the subjects of study that are about the way people think and behave, for example literature, language, history and philosophy</span><ul class=\"examples\" htag=\"ul\" hclass=\"examples\"><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"x\">The college offers a wide range of courses in the arts and humanities.</span></li></ul> <span class=\"xrefs\" htag=\"span\" hclass=\"xrefs\" xt=\"cp\"><span class=\"prefix\">compare</span> <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/science\" title=\"science definition\"><span class=\"xr-g\" bord=\"n\" href=\"science_e\"><span class=\"xh\">science</span></span></a></span><span class=\"topic-g\"><span class=\"prefix\">Topics </span><a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/education?level=c1\" title=\"Topic education\"><span class=\"topic\" href=\"l2:people:education?cefr=c1\"><span class=\"topic_name\">Education</span><span class=\"topic_cefr\">c1</span></span></a></span>      </li><div class=\"collapse\" hclass=\"collapse\" htag=\"div\"><span class=\"unbox\" unbox=\"wordorigin\" id=\"humanity_unbox_2\"><span class=\"box_title\">Word Origin</span><span class=\"body\"><span class=\"p\">Middle English: from Old French <span class=\"ei\">humanite</span>, from Latin <span class=\"ei\">humanitas</span>, from <span class=\"ei\">humanus</span>, from <span class=\"ei\">homo</span> ‘man, human being’.</span></span></span></div></ol><span class=\"dictlink-g\"><span class=\"dictlink\">See <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/american_english/humanity\" title=\" definition in American English\n \"><span class=\"xh\">humanity</span></a> in the Oxford Advanced American Dictionary</span><span class=\"dictlink\">See <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/academic/humanity\" title=\" definition in Academic English\n \"><span class=\"xh\">humanity</span></a> in the Oxford Learner's Dictionary of Academic English</span></span><div class=\"pron-link\">Check pronunciation:\n                        <a href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/pronunciation/english/humanity\">humanity</a></div></div>\n","matches":[],"relatives":[],"nearBys":["humanitarian noun","humanitarianism noun","humanity noun","humanize verb","humankind noun"]},[]]